Nvidia Corporation, founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem, began as a pioneer in graphics processing technology. Based in Santa Clara, California, the company's early mission was to enhance visual computing. In 1999, Nvidia revolutionized gaming graphics with the release of the GeForce 256, marketed as the world’s first GPU (Graphics Processing Unit), which set a new industry standard for PC graphics.

Throughout the 2000s, Nvidia expanded its influence in the gaming and professional visualization markets, acquiring key companies like 3dfx and ULI. With the advent of CUDA in 2006, Nvidia enabled GPUs to be used beyond graphics—in fields like scientific computing, AI, and data science—ushering in the era of general-purpose GPU computing.

In the 2010s, the company made significant advances with its Tegra mobile processors and deep learning platforms. Its GPUs became central to AI and machine learning research, playing a pivotal role in breakthroughs in autonomous vehicles, robotics, and high-performance computing.

In recent years, Nvidia's innovations—such as the RTX graphics cards featuring real-time ray tracing—have further cemented its leadership in gaming and AI. The company also expanded into data centers and enterprise AI, particularly with its acquisition of Mellanox Technologies in 2020.

Today, Nvidia is at the forefront of artificial intelligence, computing, and visualization technologies, continually shaping the future across gaming, AI, healthcare, and autonomous machines.

claude
